JavaScript Operator Reference


-- Arithmetic --
+ ADD     - SUBTRACT      * MULTIPLY      / DIVIDE
++ INCREMENT    -- DECREMENT

% Modulus (division remainder)
This can be used to determine whether a number is even or odd
if (i % 3 === 0) console.log('is divisible by three')
this means that if i is divisible by 3, the console will print out
'is divisible by three'

-- Assignment --
= ASSIGN value to variable
+= example x += y same as x = x + y
-= example x -= y same as x = x - y
%= example x %= y same as x = x % y

-- String --
+ will add two strings together
+= will add two strings together

-- Comparison --
== equal to (allows type cohersion)
=== equal value and type (disallows type cohersion)
!= not equal
!== not equal value or type (disallows type cohersion)
> greater than      < less than      > greater than/equal     < less than/equal


-- Conditional --
condition ? value if true : value if false
++i%3 ? '' : 'fizz'

this is checking whether the condition of ++i%3 is true
if it is, then it will print an empty string ''
if false, it will print 'fizz'

-- Logical --
&& and example (x < 10 && y > 1)      // true
|| or  example (x === 5 || y ==== 5)  // false
! not  example !(x === y)             // true

-- typeof --
typeof 'Justin' // string
typeof 2        // number
typeof false    // boolean
SPECIAL CASES
typeof NaN      // number
typeof array    // object
typeof date     // object
typeof null     // object


-- Delete -- (DON'T USE)
Deletes a property from an object
var person = {firstName: 'John', lastName: 'Smith', age: 50, eyeColor: 'blue'}
delete person.age // or delete person['age']

this will delete both the value of the property and the property itself
after deletion, the property cannot be used until it is added back
delete is designed to work on object properties. it has no effect on variables